Barack Obama wins the Nobel Peace Prize as fourth US President
U.S. President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to be the fourth U.S. President in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
In addition, he receives the diploma as well as the medal and a check of 1.4 million dollars for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northern Norwegian metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members, who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestige award.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes the prize.
The president does not want to dodge this issue because he knows he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he reinforced his war efforts by sending additional troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the Golmedal, the Diploma and the cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The program then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, with the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests attending besides Norway’s king and queen.
Obama was very restrained from the beginning of the price.
He said, for example, that he felt he didn’t deserve the price.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all those who seek the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this was "invitation to action".
