The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to stop the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured.
However, the drug composition can prolong life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral proliferation also leads to the development of resistant viruses against which no longer medicinal products are effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metalocarboranes act on the protein that is responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multivariate cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
