Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted to ban the construction of minarets and concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a sound and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's latest work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (Original title: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves") (2006), an elegant and densely argued study of a dispute that shared and occupied the country over one and a half decades and whose effects can still be perceived today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5-6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it “Islamic free spaces.”
He is a good listener, he relays debates between teachers and students about the issues that disturb them most.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or a town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up daily life, quite in contrast to the political dramas that the media engages in.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them by any known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They don’t have all the arguments on their side.
The Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who interviewed Bowen are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of puristic Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia – who nowadays show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questioned the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite so passionately guarding the separation of church and state) really felt committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who in turn had to make their historic compromise with secular Republicanism.
He sees more a "strengthening of the screws of values" than a growing pragmatism.
After reading this book, you are inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
