"In a few months... it could be us"
Marines were among the 6,000 who settled wreaths in Arlington.
Brigadier De'Angelo Robinson traveled by bus for seven hours to place a single wreath on the tomb of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other naval infantrymen who made the journey from Camp Johnson to Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the Arlington National Cemetery to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they followed.
“In a few months, wherever we are brought back from, we could be,” Robinson said of the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I would like someone to do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of the Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred tombs at the Arlington Cemetery.
It’s now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this journey every year, stop in various cities along the way to hold events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which extended the event to other states.
This year, volunteers placed more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves at Arlington Cemetery, in areas of the Pentagon, at the tombs of Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the memorial site for United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster said she took the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way to return something to those who made sacrifices.
She said this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It’s like visiting a family tomb.
Packed in places of warm clothing, the volunteers walked across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older tombs from the First and Second World Wars and the Vietnam War as their target, as these are not visited as often as the newer tombs, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children were playing and couples held hands as they carried the fresh pine branches to the greying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red loop attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is nearby and where mostly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost quiet.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 crowns to decorate this section, but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends held together in the icy air.
Some read the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black-and-white maps that had been placed in the moist mud for those whose gravestones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son’s grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio to visit the tomb of Marine Infrastructure Sub-officer David Shane Spicer, who fell in battle in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free...my son paid for it, she said.
"If I've been gone for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
U.S. government contractor arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor selling mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, foreign ministry officials said on Saturday.
The contractor, which has not yet been identified, works for Bethesda-based Development Alternatives Inc.
The company is working on projects for clients, such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
U.S. consular officials in Havana are trying to gain access to the detainee who was arrested on December 5.
The special charges have not yet been made public, although under Cuban law a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything, under the accusation of "endangerment".
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, including slight protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are being persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly asked for permission to leave the country to receive prizes, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor will likely increase tensions between the Castro Brother’s communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a “slow” approach to improving relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that the United States will provide a return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and coveted products in a country where the average earnings of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are mainly used for sending text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a daily wage.
Internet use is extremely restricted on the island.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there to foreign visitors and to some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who wish to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are sitting behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokeswoman for the U.S. Interests Office in Havana.
Berbena said she could not give further information about the arrest.
Arrest and imprisonment are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the "Human Rights Watch" group, which recently released a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, same Cuba", a reference to the inauguration of the older Fidel as the leader of the country.
Vivanco said the defendants would be very often arrested, convicted and imprisoned within a day.
He said that probably any solution would be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just as both countries are moving towards each other for more willingness to dialogue.
Pakistani government officials uncover plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities discovered on Saturday an allegedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from Northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill US soldiers, saying they hope this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruits searching the Internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said they were looking for an opaque insurgent, known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after he found them because one of them had made consenting comments on the internet video site YouTube about terrorist attacks.
Upon their arrival in Pakistan, Saifullah became the leader of these men and tried to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan’s tribal belt, which is home to Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a Pakistani intelligence official who was briefed on the matter said Saturday that Saifullah could not convince al-Qaeda leaders that the men were not part of a CIA conspiracy to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were held for days in the eastern town of Sargodha, far away from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist refuge.
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
That is why they were rejected, the government official said, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were by no means discouraged and continued to seek the right recommendations to gain access to the al-Qaeda camps when they were arrested by the Pakistani prison authorities.
The case of the five men – who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI – underscores the critical role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and possibly more importantly in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, the US intelligence service has made it a matter of utmost urgency to house human assets within Al Qaeda.
The solicitors of the organization act as gatekeepers who do not let in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American would-be recruits are undergoing a special test by A Qaeda, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to U.S. targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered to be immensely attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, the highest ranking analyst at the US-based NEFA Foundation, said terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years about who they allow access to, as U.S. intelligence services have become experts on their recruitment methods.
If you try to inject someone into these groups, what better way could you go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?, said Kohlmann.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of protesters call for climate action in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of protesters marched through the streets here on Saturday, demanding bolder action on climate action from the negotiators at the city’s Bella Congress Center.
Protesters said 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to be around 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists fired small explosives near some government buildings in downtown.
On a day when little happened at the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists wandered around the city wearing transparencies with the words “There is no Planet B” in English and one in Spanish that declared “The Earth says “Enough”.
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said that traveling to Peru, her mother’s birthplace, makes her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country is facing due to the already noticeable impacts of climate change.
That’s part of the motive why I decided to take part in the big demonstration – to spread the word and appeal to world leaders to reach a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It’s not an easy task, but it has to be done now and there’s no way around it anymore.
Police stopped protesters from getting too close to Bella Center and said they had arrested 19 people, mainly because they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to a spectator who did not want to be named because he was involved in the climate negotiations, demonstrators masked in black clothing fired several explosive bodies near the Copenhagen main canal, which is close to several ministries.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they started as luminous rockets but were then followed by “a few large explosions.”
Inside the congress center, people gathered in front of television screens to watch the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest has apparently failed to reach the awareness of key officials, such as Su Wie, China’s chief climate negotiator.
Asked if he thought the demonstration had a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: “This is something I wasn’t even aware of.”
He then went on to Mandarin and said, “Because the venue is big, I can’t hear what’s happening outside.”
He noted that it depends on the perspective of the individual whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the concentration of the general public and various sectors on the issue of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, “it can also be said that they interfere with the negotiations or the freedom of other people.”
Examination data show persistent race gap
The mathematics performance certificates were welcomed good news for the public schools in Washington D.C. last week.
Although Washington District is still far behind the nation’s top performing schools, testimonies show that fourth and eighth grades have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago, and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent performance gap between African-American and white students, both locally and nationally.
The average score of white fourth graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) over the past two years, but their African-American peers only rose by three points from 209 to 212.
The performance gap actually increased from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of African-American eighth graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average white pupil score was not included in the test data because the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was captured in that district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score that children from both groups achieved has grown over this period, the difference has barely decreased with 58 points now.
Some district education advocates expressed concern last week that the results celebrated by Chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic Mayor Adrian M. Fenty were largely driven by white students who are already high-performing children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall score by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, a board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group that advocates education equality in Washington D.C.
I don’t jump up and down for a two or three-point span, said Democratic Washington City Councilman Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in fourth grade at Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee’s management style, said the message of exam scores is that the city’s middle schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, which I respect.
But what scares me is that we don’t nearly spend the time and energy that we would have to spend on our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-performing students.
This fall, for example, some teachers will be trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at students in the upper classes of primary and middle school who have not mastered basic reading skills at the beginning of their school careers and who are significantly behind their peer-to-peer classmates.
Everyday mathematics, a curriculum that brings to the fore from kindergarten to sixth grade games and life-like experiences, has been brought to Washington under former school inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum attributes some of the NAEP progress reported last week.
I think we need to continue to work on making the best measures benefit the students who are below grade level, Rhee said.
Others say the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources for the low-performance schools that are needed to bridge the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California in Berkeley, who examines urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to target its resources and management reforms to schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could lead to political repercussions that work against this important agenda item.
The weak point, of course, is, as with other urban school inspectors, that she tries to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to make sure we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighborhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, now school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most significant elements of closing the performance gap is extending the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington to compete with charter schools.
You have to increase the school year to nearly 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teacher union last year over 185 days a year, which he considered to be "a milestone" on the way to a bigger increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people as a prospect for the future
The coach reaches the Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, gets out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white pillars, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela’s parents have barely completed high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was rescued in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Her attitude and that of the other eighth graders of the group exploring Gettysburg, where the class costs $38,690 a year, was more that of a reverend visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes, here I will be soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the guide announced that they had now entered the building for science.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when she was told of the school's low professor-to-student ratio.
College in Pennsylvania was the 7th the kids visited on their three-day tour and now they have fully received the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of children born in the United States of Hispanic immigrants who do not finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, but on the other hand there are also hundreds of thousands who receive the college education necessary to rise to the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these “second generation” of Hispanic Americans graduates from college – which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the U.S. without completing high school.
Their success stories are important, say researchers, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country’s workforce.
Those who examine high-performance children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive for success.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a big role in helping Graciela and millions of children like her get to college, especially if these efforts persist over a longer period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single measure will not solve the problem at any time, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California, Davis, who studied Hispanic students.
We need to think about providing a supportive network for these children from preschool to high school.
The federal program funded by Graciela’s College tour is a useful example.
It’s known as GEAR UP — one gear up — and provides more than $300 million a year to local school systems to start college preparatory programs that begin when low-income students are in high school and continue until they finish high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, of whom more than 60% have gone to college.
Iraqi Ministry of Oil signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns over violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to get major oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure in two auctions closed on Saturday.
The 10 contracts concluded by the Iraqi Ministry of Oil with foreign oil companies suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are willing to play an important role in renovating the Iraqi oil industry, which has been paralyzed by war and economic sanctions for decades.
American companies were only able to book shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields for themselves.
Seven American companies had paid for participating in the second auction that began on Friday.
The only company that made a bid has pulled the shortening.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly seeded representatives of American oil multitudes at the opening of the Iraqi oil industry surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war and instead of US companies, Asians and Europeans are leading the way, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no more offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns, underscored by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and political instability due to the withdrawal of the U.S. military, have likely prevented American oil companies from engaging more in Iraq, which holds the world’s third-largest proven crude oil reserves.
U.S. companies were disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to hold shareholders accountable.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only U.S. companies that were able to enter into contracts with the ministry.
Larger U.S. companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which maintain close ties with the Iraqi Ministry of Oil and have supported technical advice in recent years, have gone empty.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation has offered for more contracts than any other company and was able to go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, the Ministry of Oil spokesman Assam Jihad said, that China is on its way to becoming one of the majors in the world economy as well as a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company will be able to compete with its competitors and will meet its commitments to Iraq.
Pre-selected companies placed bids for the bid, which were then compared to the fee per barrel of oil that the Ministry was willing to pay to increase the emission of each field beyond the current level.
Al Qaeda top planner reportedly killed in Pakistan
In an obvious U.S. missile attack along the Pakistani border with Afghanistan, a top Al Qaeda deployment planner was reportedly killed this week, U.S. counter-terrorism officials reported on Friday.
This, if confirmed, would be the second deadly attack on a senior terrorist organization official this fall.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arabs who, according to US sources and Pakistani officials in the region, were killed by a number of missiles that hit their vehicle near the city of Miran Shah in northern Waziristan province on Tuesday.
Local authorities reported that the missiles were fired by a type of drone used by the CIA in Pakistan’s lawless tribal belt.
They were driving in a white vehicle towards the Afghan border when the car was hit, an official of a Pakistani civilian intelligence service from Miran Shah said by phone.
Locals suspected of belonging to the militants ran to the site and quickly took in everything that was left of the "completely destroyed bodies."
Local authorities could not confirm the identity of the victims, but two U.S. counterterrorism officials cited indefinite evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somalia has been described as the leading military planner of Al Qaeda, which led operations of terrorist groups outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracies around the world, noted a senior official who wanted to remain anonymous, pointing to the sensitive nature of the US airstrikes on Pakistani soil.
Assuming its central role as given, this also included planning attacks against the US and Europe.
He accepted strategic instructions from the top leaders of Al Qaeda and implemented them in operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second U.S. official said that Somali had quickly risen in the al-Qaeda hierarchy and had best ties to other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, the second official said, but this in no way diminishes the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death was confirmed, Somali would be the second leading Al Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September when Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal territory, and three other top activists were killed in a similar attack.
The pace of CIA drone attacks has declined from an average of six operations per month to two since the summer, according to a summary in the Long War Journal, a website run by a nonprofit organization.
The decline may be due to improved tactics by terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the site reported.
Leading UN envoy in Kabul will resign
The UN’s top envoy to Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday he would step down from office in March, ending a stormy term clouded by claims of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
The Obama administration has decided to send another 30,000 US troops to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supported the troop increase, but he also expressed concern that the U.S. military withdrawal schedule, which is set to begin in 18 months, could prompt other NATO governments to withdraw their armed forces.
We must accelerate the construction of the Afghan security forces and thus send the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, Eide said in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian aides to help in Afghanistan’s political transition.
The increase in troops on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said he did not step down from office, but only fulfilled an agreement made in March 2008 with his family to stay in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted to send a message to the United Nations.
Secretary General Ban Ki-moon is now forwarding so that he has time to arrange for a replacement.
What I’ve said is that he’s better off starting to look for a successor, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
According to UN officials, Ban has begun searching for a replacement.
The UN officials say that he has considered the Swedish-Italian-original Staffan di Mistura, who recently led the UN mission in Baghdad and the Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously led UN peace operations.
His position in Afghanistan was tested after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country’s presidential election and covering up evidence of massive election fraud.
Eide has rejected all allegations, but he also said that the allegations of Galbraith - who was fired - "undoubtedly harmed the mission because there was already a great deal of skepticism regarding international interference in the election."
Eide said he recommended the appointment of a senior civil representative to coordinate the relief efforts of the American-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN leadership to allow his successor to hire more personnel from the United States and other Western countries to donate to the Afghan mission, saying this would strengthen their confidence in their money being used properly.
Eide expressed his disappointment at the limitation of his forces in Afghanistan, saying that the cumbersome UN hiring regulations have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed in such a way that since May, he said, I have only been able to hire one person.
This is disastrous and must not continue like this.
U.S. Defense Secretary Gates: Iran must expect additional sanctions
Defense Minister Robert M. Gates said Friday that world powers will soon impose “significant additional sanctions” on Iran because it has not participated in talks about its nuclear plans.
During a seven-day trip through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, Gates spoke to a group of about 300 U.S. soldiers in northern Iraq and downplayed the prospect of a military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
In Iran, there are no good options to choose from, he said in response to a soldier’s question about the likelihood of such development.
“One of the things that is on my mind is that in the last six years we have learned something from Iraq that is unpredictable to war.”
The Obama administration is considering a sanctions package aimed at Iran’s military and political elite, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the average Iranian.
He said that a “package of positive and negative incentives” is needed “to convince the Iranian government that it is in reality less protected with nuclear weapons” because “its people will suffer tremendously” from the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement by White House spokesman Robert Gibbs, the U.S. government joined European top politicians in warning that Iran must expect “credible” consequences if it fails to comply with the demands of the UN Security Council and its nuclear watchdog, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran continues to claim that nuclear technology knowledge is only to be gained for peaceful purposes.
At talks in Geneva on October 1, Iran said it would resume talks to restrict its nuclear program and renounce a substantial part of its stockpile of enriched uranium in exchange for much-needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The U.S. government has pushed for this kind of agreement to build trust between the two parties and gain time for negotiations.
But Iran seems to have left negotiations on the interim agreements since then -- in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership disagrees about whether they should commit to the United States.
That Iran has simply left the international community behind in terms of some of the proposals it had already agreed to in early October has, frankly, brought the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, together in a way they have never been in connection with important additional sanctions on Iran, Gates said.
President Obama has set the 31st of December as a deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before pursuing other options, including those that Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called “suppressing sanctions.”
In a statement issued in New York, Iran’s representation at the United Nations condemned what it called Thursday “unfounded and unfounded claims” by some Security Council members about Iran’s nuclear activities and said they were ready to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers “to achieve an appropriate long-term solution.”
Gates, who was due to return to Washington last Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki in the morning before flying to the oil-rich Kurdish region in Iraq to meet with soldiers in Kirkuk and with Kurdish officials in Irbil.
Tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq continue to be high, particularly in terms of borders, property rights and the distribution of public revenues.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict in order to prevent delays in US plans to reduce US troops from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also tried to dispel Kurdish concern about the imminent troop withdrawal. U.S. officials quoted Gates as saying to Masud Barzani, president of the Kurdish regional government: "We will preserve your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a united Iraq.
We will not leave you.”
A change of course in the aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that gave them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One baby more means a grave more".
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course due to the low birth rate and the aging population this summer, encouraging young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and definitive: "Not at all."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There’s nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has brought forth two generations of notoriously thick, distorted single children lovingly called “little emperors,” a population crisis is rising in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, according to the UN.
Department of Population Issues is expected to explode from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 percent by 2020, well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older adults accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, said that couples of capable age need to have babies to “help reduce the ratio of the aging population and alleviate the labour shortage of the future.”
"Shanghai will soon be as old -- but not as rich -- as developed countries like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A step-by-step relaxation
