UN Group develops emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- re-emphasized on Friday with the release of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrial nations having to shoulder the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a time-out negotiation as more than 100 top politicians from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can master global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to put the spotlight on what the UN’s leading climate representative, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted the talks on Friday by pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from overcoming floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
U.S. Climate Special Representative Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for mandatory reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging markets, if these are not financed by industrialized nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration is on a tougher line with China than the Bush administration had two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging markets rising up and taking action, according to Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei’s statement that the leading American climate negotiator was either lacking “reason” or “highly irresponsible” that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China to cope with global warming.
With the future economic march direction of the great world powers at stake, broken lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the big powers are struggling over who should bear the cost of stopping greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to take more aggressive steps to hold countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, according to Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leaders say the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states’ offensive “is exerting political pressure on the entire political process,” partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the open issues need to be clarified before the arrival of the leaders of the government to reach an agreement.
High-level representatives, such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Deputy Minister, stepped out of their planes and rushed through the Bella Center’s corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to settle claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer magnitude of the gathering -- 13,000 people walk in and out of the congress center every day, guitar-playing activists hold night shows making fun of the countries they think betray and sell, and draft contracts are hand-to-hand instead of email -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all the major ministers are here now and from Wednesday will be 60 government leaders in Copenhagen.
“We’re coming to the top league,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
