Border State Between Dream and Hallucination
In our overly consciousness-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, distressing disease, but it also holds positive, creative – madness is also a work of art from despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-changed waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self-loss and world loss, for example, by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of meaningful foundation and meaningfulness in an inherently unbearable situation, which allows us human beings our own ability not to perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
