75% of working mothers have problems at work due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fruchtbarkeit und Karriere von Frauen in Spanien", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited because of their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether or not the women work and if so, what type of profession they practice.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half-days or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sector, postpone the formation of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed job get their first child on average only 3.7 years after reunification, a number that rises to 4.1 years for women with a fixed job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only realized their reunification and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar with regard to the willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account at the age of women at the time of marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they have only a primary school degree or a higher education, became mothers for the first time, on average, with 25.1 or 32.1 each.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a major degree get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly differently and only seek a permanent job and marry afterwards and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
